segments.text: Well, what do you feel probably was the most important thing that you did while you were at A&M, the most important of all the things we've discussed, that had the greatest?
You're talking about me personally?
Mm-hmm, you.
Well, I think you're right.

Over the many years that I worked here, the thing that was most important was that I had a part in some of the organizations and changes in attitude about communications from the student to the top and then from the top down to the student.
This is manifested by the fact that we had a counseling program for the first time.
We had a testing program.
We had a good organized loan program.
And I didn't do this myself, but I was one of the people that worked on it all the time with many others, counselors, and chief of housing, and the dean, and some of the academic people.
and Wayne Stark in the Memorial Student Center.
We worked with him a lot on some of these things.
And we got a lot of programs started that had never been instituted at A&M.
And we think all of these things, through the long pull, kept student attitude good.
And it's given them better education.
Well, just like in our discipline attitude, we didn't just call them in and tell them they'd been bad boys and we were going to kick them out of school.
But we didn't ever say we'd kick you out.
We'd say you're suspended for a period of time, that you go out and reflect and think about this.
We never closed the door on the guy.
Now, when I came here, we found a lot of students that had been dismissed, and this meant they couldn't ever come back.
One of the first things that I did was went to the president, Mr. Gilkes, and I said, Mr. Gilkes, now here's a guy, a good guy, I know him, but I've talked to him a number of times.
He's been dismissed from A&M, and he's been told he can't ever come back, but he wants to finish his education.
And I'd like to go before the executive committee and plea for these guys, because it isn't right to kick a kid out of school and say he can't ever go back again.
Just for one mistake.
So the executive committee, now this is,

I got to take pride in that because we did this as a Dean of Students organization and I was the speaker for them and Mr. Gilkes joined with me and he plugged for this at the executive committee and they voted to let every one of you guys back in school.
Every one of them was readmitted and so far as I know only one man since that time has been dismissed from A&M.
We changed, we had, we kept meticulous and minute detailed records for a long time.
And we finally found out that this is hurting students.
And we had a confidential file that we needed to keep.
But we, before I left that office over there, I got permission from the dean to destroy two or three, two and a half time truckloads of records.
because they had a lot of little things about students when they were freshmen and sophomores that could be held against them for a lifetime.
And they were not serious enough.
They were bad, like lying and cheating and stealing and getting drunk and beating up some poor old guy downtown or something like that.
We didn't think this was bad, but it's not enough to jeopardize a guy for a lifetime.
So I think through the years that this is the thing that a lot of us, Mr. Gilchrist, I'd say was a predominant figure in this kind of an attitude, and Mr.
Rudder, Dean Hannigan, Ken Berthe, Bob Kahn, Doe Rollins, Bob Murray, WG Brazil, Perry, Melcher,
Oates.
I could probably name some others, but these are guys that were dedicated to this.
And we talked about it, and we talked to a lot of other people and got their support.
But all of these things have helped, not completely, but helped develop a good publication board and a good
to a publication program and all of these other things like placement and loan and so on.
I don't know whether that answers your question or not.
I think that does a pretty good job of it.
Well, we certainly appreciate it.
I think you've covered lots of ground.
Well, I hope you find something in there that might be good for your records.
